Introduction : Is the videogame industry important?

The gaming industry is a 90 billion USD worth business that has shown increasing growth over the last decade. Through different scenarios, such as the recent COVID-19 pandemic, its spotlight and relevance has only increased. This remarkable growth has recently been ignited more by the two biggest players Sony and Microsoft due to the launch of the next gen consoles PS5 and XBOX Series X, which has established a revolutionary change in the industry as it is expected in the 7-year next-gen cycle. This creates several speculations about the impact into console gaming and the potential that it can acquire within the next years for all of the online gaming sector.

This project aimed to analyze the historical data obtained in video game unit sales for the previous decades; starting from a general point of view, including all consoles and all games, narrowing it down to PS4 and XBOX One performance in the past years. The analysis aimed to showcase the importance of gaming, its correlation between certain variables such as Genre, Platform or Publisher, and it will allow the hypothesis to be tested by evaluating the impact of new consoles in the gaming industry.

Given the findings in our research and plots, it was found a potential relationship between platform,publisher and genre. Some platform contain specific genres that are preferred by their customers data base and therefore, this bring significant information towards developers and the gaming industry in general.

This has several implications as to developing exclusive games for one console with a popular genre, it determines specific deals with well-known publishers and franchises. Basically, it proves that there is impact between theses factors in the gaming industry.

Data

We use the dataset videogames sales from kaggle : “https://www.kaggle.com/sidtwr/videogames-sales-dataset”

We will use the following datasets:

  1. Video Games Sales as 22 Dec 2016
  2. PS4 Games Sales
  3. Xbox One Games Sales

The dataset will allow the analysis of new video game hardware release impact in the gaming industry. As the historical impact into the gaming ecosystem is analyzed, it can be useful towards new hardware launches analysis. Specifically, in this dataset, the consoles to be analyzed will be PS4, XBOX, and Wii.

videogames = read_csv("Video_Games_Sales_as_at_22_Dec_2016.csv")
ps4_data = read_csv("PS4_GamesSales (2).csv")
xbox_data= read_csv("XboxOne_GameSales (1).csv")

Exploratory Analysis

Initial Hypothesis

  1. Ho: Games with carefully picked Genre, Publisher and Platform have no impact towards total unit sales.
  2. Ha: Games with carefully picked Genre, Publisher and Platform have impact towards total unit sales.

The following plot showcases the best game selling console: the PS2 and we focus on the most selling genre: Action, Sports and Shooter. A limitation to be noted into these graphic is that it doesn’t reflect the full life cycle of the PS4 and Xbox One, this data could evolve and change the plot, the global sales is on million of units sold. There is some evidence the platform influences the sales of some titles of the same genre.

videogames %>% 
  filter(Genre==c('Action','Sports','Shooter')) %>% 
  ggplot(data =.) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = Platform,y=Global_Sales,fill=Genre),stat="identity")+
  facet_wrap(~Genre)+coord_flip()

We focus our attention in two majot players Sony and Microsoft with the playstation and Xbox platform. We notice 3 of the platform present a game with over 20 million copies sold. We need to examine these outliers since these best sold games translate into the success of the new platform.

videogames %>%
  na.omit() %>% 
  filter(Year_of_Release > 2000, Platform %in% c("PS","PS2","PS3","PS4","X360","XOne","XB")) %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x =Platform,y=Global_Sales)) + 
  geom_boxplot()+coord_flip()

On the following plot we analyze the impact of games sold, when a new platform was launched, we focus the analysis on playstation and Xbox and 3 main genres: Action, Shooter and Sports.

On the graph we can notice a small impact on the last years of the 90’s, However after the 2000 and 2001 when the PS2 and Xbox was launch there is a big peak of the units sold specially on the action genre.

2005 and 2006 does not show a big impact on the overall sales (ps3 and Xbox360), maybe these platforms did not had a good marketing method or the impact of the Wii launch on that exact year that greatly impact the sales on other platforms. However there is a recovery on the following years duplicating the amount of games sales and a huge peak after 2010 when new editions of these platforms were launched.

Finally a big peak on 2013 when both manufactures launched their latest platforms PS4 and Xbox One, having sales of 20M units sold only that year. We can conclude that there is a relation between units sold and the years the platforms were launched.

To continue the analysis, we need to reject the nulll hypothesis that sales are independent of the platform, since we want to find out if there is any impact on the general sales when a new console is launched.

We use the most important market for video games: The US. As dependent variable we use the sales on the rest of the world and the main platforms.

When we run this regression, we found that the sales on the other regions ( EU, Japan and Rest of the World) have a positive impact on the sales in the US, this can be due to the buzz a game generates in another region making more likable for the American market to embrace it.

On the other hand, the playstation platform has a negative impact on the overall american sales, this is because the most use console in the US is the Xbox, while in Europe is Playstation, this impact is statistically significant and appears with every version of the console.

As expected the Xbox has a positive impact on the NA sales, however is surprising the Wii also affects in a positive way the overall sales, but this can be cause by the many titles that are unique for Nintendo.

We can reject the null hypthesis, were we stablish sales are independent of platform we have a p-value close to zero and a R2=0.76

videogames %>% 
  filter( Platform %in% c("PS","PS2","PS3","PS4","X360","Wii","XOne","XB")) %>% 
  lm(formula = NA_Sales~EU_Sales+JP_Sales+Other_Sales+Platform,data=.) %>% 
  summary()
